>For Classics made from 1990 or older, although exceptions are made for cars with a body style that started after 1990
>Everybody has their own taste, but some tastes are wrong. If you aren't sure if your car is classic or not, it's not.

>US, Euro, Jap, or whatever.
>Post your classic, your work on it, your hackery, and get advice.
>Any and all discussion about classics welcome, but may not necessarily generate responses; don't get butthurt.
>Period correct performance > cosmetics.
>Metal > plastic.
>Classic shitbox > modern shitbox.
>JBweld and RTV can fix anything
>If you see rust there is more.
>Rust and bodywork are the most difficult thing to repair.
>Electrical work is difficult until you stop reading forum posts and buy a multimeter.

It’s the best engine for daily use. Reports coming in everywhere say that stock pushrod V8 coupled with stock automatic transmission is the most reliable powertrain in the world. People have driven these engines for a million miles without opening them.
Not dissing Europeans, we can make amazing race engines. Germans, Brits and Italians made some of the best DOHC engines ever. But these things are not made to last. They were made to compete with other manufacturers, to have the highest revs and HP.

com:
GM unveiled a huge new lineup of full-sizer cars for 1971. The Cadillac versions swelled to a 130" wheelbase and 5,000 pound curb weight. Topping the line was the Sixty Special, riding a 133" wheelbase, the largest mass production American car ever built. Convertible models did not return, leaving Cadillac soft tops exclusively to the Eldorado until getting the axe in 1975 as part of a general Detroit phase-out of convertibles. Standard drivetrain was the 472 V8, now detuned to be compatible with emissions hardware. Styling changes over six model years were mostly detail and concerned changes to the grille and the adoption of now legalized square headlight on '76 models. For 1974 the addition of 5 mph bumpers and catalytic converters added still more curb weight. Due to this added bulk the Eldorado's 500 cid V8 was made standard in C and D-body Cadillacs.

But size had clearly gotten out of hand, and soon after the new full-sizers arrived in showrooms during fall 1970, GM was making plans for a downsized successor, and the OPEC embargo in late 1973-early '74 accelerated the project.

com:
The redoubtable Kenosha, Wisconsin-based Nash introduced their new postwar models for 1949. The Airflyte was one of the more radical designs of the era, replacing the company's entirely conventional-looking 1941-48 models with a large, bulbous new vehicle. Emphasis was on safety and comfort, sporting a padded "safety" dashboard sporting a large instrument pod that combined all gauges in one unit, and a huge interior with fold-down rear seats that could be made into a bed (as such these Nashes were said to be the dread of every teenage daughter's parents). Performance was not an emphasis, with Nash's 172 cid I6, making 112 hp at the wheels, being the only drivetrain offered. Nash also boasted of the car's excellent fuel economy, good for up to 30 mpg, and long range due to the 20 gallon fuel tank (claimed range was up to 500 miles). They had offered I8s in the past but they didn't return after civilian car production resumed in late 1945. Only a sedan and coupe were offered, in either base 600 or high trim Ambassador models.

The bulbous 49-51 Nash styling, also shared by the contemporary Lincoln Cosmopolitan, was a period fad that became dated quickly and disappeared with the more blocky 1952 models.

Such a thing would increase power and efficiency and in the first example add utility to the old FWD cars. Then it would be a matter of matching the throttle input front and rear, and using either Regen to top off the battery and or have a high voltage alternator added to the engine bay. Its 2015, GTR vs Corvette is at its peak, since 2007 everyone on /o/ is going mental over who will lap the nuburgring faster, one year its the cuckvette, the next year is the GTR, and so on. Every version has already been tested, the facelift GTR, the z07, the zr1, just imagine this, a nurburgring thread easily reached 400 replies daily. Then Nissan releases the Nismo, 7:08, people were going fucking insane, cuckvette fans having meltdowns daily, butthurt was off the charts. it was even faster than the ACR viper, No one could fucking belive it. Cuckevtte fanboys then start shitposting about how the next one will win and so on, they benchrace about skidpad numbers, horsepower, weight, you name it, the cuckvete had the advantage on every single measure.
we all knew that the z06 would dominate, it should dominate, its a brand new car, its better in every single way, yet it failed. We are not talking about being slower around some irrelevant track in Asia or with an irrelevant magazine. It was on motortrend, on fucking motortrend, a brand new corvette got LITERALLY destroyed by an old pigfat boat. every single american who is into cars saw the video, it was literally national shame, /o/ was on fire

If you go to the previous videos they released, where they test the cars separatedly, the comment section is full of corvette fangirls saying how the Corvette would dominate, yet when you go to the comparison, you see them begging for mercy. And to add salt to the wound, it failed to deliver at the Driver's car competition, a brand new car, out due to overheating issues

The corvette got absolutely fucking rekt, it got destroyed, there is simply no way around it, no ifs or buts, there is literally no way GM fangirls can control the damae. It was a massacre and even today it still causes a little assmad here and there. It ended almost a decade of shitposting, the GTR was faster. thats it, its faster than the Corvette, it won.
